			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2014</a> paper:</span><br><i>Respect Your Parents: How Attribution and Rewriting Can Get Along</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AnthonyMSloane.html">Anthony M. Sloane</a>, <a href="../profile/MatthewRoberts.html">Matthew Roberts</a>, <a href="../profile/LenHamey.html">Len Hamey</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_11">10.1007/978-3-319-11245-9_11</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagM">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> It studies attribute grammars as a metalanguage for defining context-dependent computations on trees.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> It addresses interactions between attribution and rewriting, i.e., tree transformation mechanisms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1c.html"><span class="tagL">T1C: Behavioural Semantics</span></a><ul><li> It formalizes semantic issues around context dependence when trees are rewritten during evaluation.
</li></ul></li></ul>
